Question: can we rely on nh.now() to provide accurate timestamps on an arduino over rosserial?

Method: publish timeref messages from teensy, where header time is derived from nh.now(), and time_ref is derived from micros(). Compare nh.now() timestamps to micros - micros should be very dependable

allMsgs = list(rosbag.Bag('timeRefLogging__2019-01-27-19-34-17.bag').read_messages())
timeDf = pd.DataFrame([
    dict(
        microsTime = msg.time_ref.to_time(),
        rosTime = msg.header.stamp.to_time()
    ) for _, msg,_ in allMsgs
])

timeDf['dMicrosTime'] = timeDf.microsTime.diff()
timeDf['dRosTime'] = timeDf.rosTime.diff()
timeDf['elapsedSeconds'] = timeDf.microsTime - timeDf.microsTime.min()

Conclusions:¶

The micros() based time does appears more dependable, as the nh.now() timestamps have many jumps (errors), often by 1 ms, and sometimes in the order of a few milliseconds.

So I assume that using nh.now() will introduce occasional timestamp errors in the range of a few milliseconds.

I assume the regular 1ms errors in nh.now() indicate that the clock has millisecond precision, and that the larger errors relate to ongoing synchronisation with the PC.

The micros clock forgoes this ongoing synchronisation, and so will drift from the PC clock over larger timeframes, but comes with the advantage of providing high relative accuracy between consequtive timestamps.
